commit.message:
Release 2.0.1

Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <stephen@that.guru>

Add changelog for 2.0.1

Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <stephen@that.guru>

Use poetry-core as the build backend

Use poetry-core rather than poetry as the build backend.  This
is the recommended upstream solution, as it produces the same end result
while not requiring the tools to install the complete set of poetry
dependencies while building the wheel, effectively making the builds
much faster.

See "Why is this required?" at https://pypi.org/project/poetry-core/

Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <stephen@that.guru>

trivial: Update poetry.lock ordering

Seems poetry has changed the ordering of the poetry.lock file at some
point in the past (using poetry 1.1.13 from the repos on Fedora 36).
Fortunately, unlike in the past [1], it now versions this file so future
changes should be less likely (see the '[metadata] lock-version' value
added here). It's debatable that we should even be committing this for a
library like warlock [2], but as long as this is here we have to live
with it. Commit an "update" thus correcting this ordering. This will
allow us to see the actual diff in a future change.

[1] https://stackoverflow.com/q/65625717
[2] https://stackoverflow.com/q/61037557

Undo changes to the `warlock.model_factory` API

The changes introduced by commit 64a771d151a5defb9bca82042f ("Allow
resolver to be set on the Model") added a new keyword argument to the
`warlock.model_factory` function. Due to the way Python handles
positional arguments, the change alters the way that existing code is
interpreted.

Before the change,

    warlock.model_factory(schema_arg, snd_pos_arg)

would execute with

    kwargs == {
        'base_class': snd_pos_arg,
        'name': None,
    }

but after the change it's interpreted as

    kwargs == {
        'resolver': snd_pos_arg,
        'base_class'=model.Model,
        'name': None,
    }

This commit re-arranges the arguments to restore the previous behaviour
in an effort to not break existing code.
